PATIENTS AND METHODS: The study included 26 adults (median age 38.5 years, range 18-80) from two unrelated MEN-1 pedigrees. In 15 of the patients the diagnosis was confirmed by genetic analysis, while in the rest the diagnosis was based on clinical criteria combined with genealogy data.
