	abstract = {Epstein–Barr virus-positive T/NK-cell lymphoproliferative diseases (EBV-T/NK-LPDs) include several overlapping EBV-related conditions with variably aggressive courses. For prognostic categorization, we retrospectively analyzed 42 EBV-T/NK-LPD cases. Male (79\% [33/42]), young ( 40 years; 83\% [35/42]) patients and T-cell lineage (81\% [34/42]; CD8/CD4 ¼ 1.8) were predominant. Clinicopathologically, three systemic and one cutaneous category were developed: hemophagocytic lymphohistiocytosis (HLH; 26\% [11/42]), chronic active EBV infection (CAEBV; 31\% [13/42]), systemic unclassifiable disease (24\% [10/42]), and hydroa vacciniforme/hydroa vacciniforme-like lymphoma (HV/HVL; 19\% [8/42]). Prognostically, cutaneous disease (HV/HVL) was better than systemic disease (p ¼ 0.014; median, 285 vs. 10 months). In systemic diseases, HLH was worst (p ¼ 0.002; 3[HLH] vs. 4[unclassifiable] vs. not reached [CAEBV]). Univariate survival analysis (n ¼ 42) revealed cytopenia (!one lineage; p {\textless} 0.001), onset age ({\textgreater}40 years; p ¼ 0.001), T-cell lineage (p ¼ 0.041), hemophagocytic histiocytes (p ¼ 0.031), elevated lactate dehydrogenase (p ¼ 0.020), and liver dysfunction (p ¼ 0.023) predicted shorter survival. In multivariate analysis, T-cell lineage (p ¼ 0.025 [HR ¼11.3]) and cytopenia (p ¼ 0.028 [HR ¼5.4]) were independent prognostic factors. Therefore, EBV-T/NK-LPD could be classified into four prognostic categories.},
