RESULTS: The concentration of 8-isoprostane was increased in patients with sarcoidosis compared to control subjects (mean, 64.23 pg/mL; 95\% confidence interval [CI], 37.00 to 91.46 pg/mL; vs mean, 20.75 pg/mL; 95\% CI, 16.06 to 25.44 pg/mL; p = 0.04). The difference was primarily due to the patients with active disease, who had significantly higher levels of 8-isoprostane (mean, 111.4 pg/mL; 95\% CI, 62.56 to 160.30 pg/mL; p {\textless} 0.001) compared to patients with nonactive disease (mean, 22.94 pg/mL; 95\% CI, 15.89 to 29.99 pg/mL) or healthy subjects. 8-Isoprostane levels in patients with nonactive disease did not differ from those in healthy subjects (p {\textgreater} 0.05). In the patients with sarcoidosis, 8-isoprostane levels were positively correlated with sACE level (p {\textless} 0.0001, r = 0.69), but was not correlated with serum calcium level or pulmonary function test values.
